  "intro": "Direct object pronouns work the same with irregular verbs. The verb form may be irregular, but the pronoun still goes before the conjugated verb in simple sentences.",
  "overview": {
    "body": "With verbs like tener, poner, hacer, decir, traer, poder, querer, saber, and venir, keep the pronoun placement steady: lo tengo, la pongo, lo hago, te vengo a buscar.",
    "use_note": "direct object pronouns with irregular verbs"
  },
  "examples": [
    {
      "spanish": "Tengo el pasaporte. Lo tengo.",
      "english": "I have the passport. I have it."
    },
    {
      "spanish": "Hago la tarea. La hago.",
      "english": "I do the homework. I do it."
    }
  ],
  "uses": [
    {
      "heading": "Replace a repeated noun",
      "body": "Use lo, la, los, or las when the object is already clear.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "spanish": "Tengo el boleto. Lo tengo.",
          "english": "I have the ticket. I have it."
        },
        {
          "spanish": "Compro las entradas. Las compro.",
          "english": "I buy the tickets. I buy them."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "People can be direct objects",
      "body": "Use me, te, nos, lo, la, los, or las for people who receive the action directly.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "spanish": "Ana me ayuda.",
          "english": "Ana helps me."
        },
        {
          "spanish": "Yo te escucho.",
          "english": "I listen to you."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
